APPENDIX D: TECHNOLOGY SPECIFICATIONS

D.1 HITL CHAOS ARENA TECHNICAL DRAWINGS

Overall Dimensions:

· Total area: 100m × 50m × 20m (height)
· Divided into 4 quadrants with movable partitions
· Floor: 30cm deep regolith simulant over metal grating
· Walls: Projection surfaces (360° immersive displays)
· Ceiling: Gantry system with 10-ton capacity

Quadrant 1: Mechanical Systems Graveyard

· Contents: Decommissioned spacecraft components
  · 2 × Orion capsule mockups (partial)
  · 1 × SpaceX Dragon pressure vessel
  · 3 × ISS module segments
  · Assorted thrusters, gyros, solar array mechanisms
· Special features: Pneumatic shakers to simulate vibration, thermal blankets with programmable heaters/coolers

Quadrant 2: Electronics Corrosion Chamber

· Environment: Controlled humidity (0-80%), temperature (-50°C to +80°C)
· Contaminants: Regolith simulant with variable electrostatic charge
· Test articles: Circuit boards, sensors, connectors, displays
· Monitoring: 50-channel data acquisition system, thermal cameras

Quadrant 3: Vacuum/Thermal Cycling Rig

· Chamber: 5m diameter spherical vacuum chamber
· Capabilities: 10⁻⁷ torr vacuum, -200°C to +150°C
· Ports: 20 electrical feedthroughs, 4 optical viewports
· Airlock: Class 100 cleanroom compatible
· Safety: Triple redundant pressure sensors, automatic repressurization

Quadrant 4: Deliberate Sabotage Workshop

· Tools for instructors to introduce faults:
  · Component substitution (incorrect parts)
  · Wiring modifications (crossed connections)
  · Software corruption (bit flips, memory errors)
  · Mechanical interference (added friction, misalignment)
· All modifications logged in blockchain for audit trail

Control Room Specifications:

· 10 operator stations, each with:
  · 6 × 4K displays
  · Haptic feedback controls
  · Biometric monitoring of students
  · AI assistant for scenario management
· Central "God view" display wall (10m × 3m)
· Recording: 50 camera angles, all data streams, audio from all locations

D.2 DIGITAL TWIN ARCHITECTURE SPECIFICATIONS

Hardware Platform:

Wearable Module (Student Issue):

· Processor: Custom neuromorphic chip (1M neurons)
· Memory: 32GB LPDDR5, 1TB NVMe storage
· Sensors:
  · 64-channel dry EEG headset
  · PPG heart rate monitor (wrist)
  · Galvanic skin response (finger sensors)
  · IMU (9-axis motion tracking)
  · Microphone array (voice + respiratory analysis)
  · Thermopile array (facial temperature mapping)
· Connectivity: Wi-Fi 6E, UWB for precise location, satellite backup
· Battery: 48-hour operation, wireless charging
· Durability: IP68, radiation hardened to 100 krad

Station Module (Workstation Integration):

· Processor: 64-core ARM v9 with AI accelerators
· Memory: 256GB HBM3, 8TB SSD
· Displays: 3 × 8K AR/VR capable
· Input: Eye tracking, gesture recognition, haptic gloves
· Security: Quantum-resistant encryption module, hardware root of trust

Habitat Module (Central Server):

· Cluster: 100 nodes, each 128-core with 4 AI accelerators
· Storage: 10PB all-flash array with 100GB/s throughput
· Networking: 400GbE backbone, optical switching
· Uptime: 99.999% via N+2 redundancy
· Power: 100kW continuous, battery backup for 24 hours

Software Stack:

Layer 1: Sensory Interface

```
Components:
- BioSignal Processor: Real-time EEG/ECG/GSR analysis
- Environmental Integrator: Habitat sensor fusion
- Natural Language Processor: Multimodal voice understanding
- Motion Tracker: Skeletal and fine motor movement analysis
```

Layer 2: Cognitive Modeling

```
Components:
- Learning Style Classifier: Adapts presentation based on cognitive preferences
- Stress Predictor: Anticipates cognitive degradation under load
- Decision Pattern Analyzer: Maps reasoning approaches
- Memory Augmentation: Contextual recall assistance
```

Layer 3: Operational Support

```
Components:
- Procedure Automator: Executes routine tasks
- Anomaly Detector: Identifies deviations from expected patterns
- Scenario Simulator: Runs "what-if" analyses
- Knowledge Base: Integrated access to all training materials
```

Layer 4: Ethical Sentinel

```
Components:
- Constraint Checker: Validates decisions against ethical frameworks
- Intervention Advisor: Suggests course corrections
- Explanation Generator: Provides rationale for suggestions
- Audit Logger: Tamper-proof record of all decisions and recommendations
```

Data Architecture:

· All data encrypted end-to-end
· Local processing for sensitive biometric data
· Federated learning across digital twins (privacy preserving)
· Daily backup to off-site secure facility
· 10-year retention policy for all data

D.3 NEURO-FEEDBACK EQUIPMENT REQUIREMENTS

EEG Systems (20 suites required):

· Manufacturer: BrainProducts GmbH
· Model: LiveAmp 64 with actiCAP
· Channels: 64 active electrodes (10-20 system plus extensions)
· Sampling rate: 1000 Hz (up to 10,000 Hz optional)
· Input noise: <0.4 μV RMS
· Connectivity: Wireless (Bluetooth 5.2) with optical isolation
· Software: BrainVision Recorder/PyCorder plus custom LAEP software

fNIRS Systems (10 suites required):

· Manufacturer: NIRx Medical Technologies
· Model: NIRSport2 8x8
· Channels: 32 sources, 32 detectors (128 channels)
· Wavelengths: 760 nm and 850 nm dual-wavelength
· Sampling rate: Up to 100 Hz
· Software: Aurora with custom hemodynamic analysis plugins

Transcranial Stimulation (5 devices):

· Manufacturer: Neuroelectrics
· Model: Starstim tES/tDCS/tACS
· Channels: 8 independent current sources
· Current range: 0-4 mA per channel
· Waveforms: DC, AC (1-250 Hz), random noise
· Safety: Impedance monitoring, automatic shutoff
· Targeting: MRI-guided individual optimization

Peripheral Monitoring:

· Heart rate variability: Polar H10 with 1ms accuracy
· Galvanic skin response: Shimmer3 GSR+ unit
· Pupillometry: Tobii Pro Spectrum 600 Hz
· Facial EMG: Delsys Trigno Avanti with 4 EMG sensors
· Respiration: Respiband Professional (thoracic/abdominal)

Integration Requirements:

· All systems must synchronize to microsecond accuracy
· Real-time data streaming to central AI at <10ms latency
· Redundant recording on local and central systems
· Calibration protocols before each use
· Weekly validation against gold standard systems

Safety Protocols:

· Maximum tDCS current: 2 mA (below perceptual threshold)
· Continuous impedance monitoring during stimulation
· Emergency stop buttons at each station
· Daily inspection of all electrodes and connectors
· Monthly certification by biomedical engineering staff

D.4 LIFE SUPPORT SYSTEM DESIGNS

Primary Habitat Life Support (Capacity: 32 persons):

Air Revitalization System:

· CO₂ removal: 4-bed molecular sieve (alternating adsorption/desorption)
· Capacity: 2.3 kg CO₂/day/person × 32 = 73.6 kg/day total
· O₂ generation: Solid electrolyte electrolysis (NASA SBIR Phase III)
· Capacity: 0.84 kg O₂/day/person × 32 = 26.9 kg/day total
· Trace contaminant control: Activated carbon + catalytic oxidation
· Monitoring: Continuous multi-gas analyzer (O₂, CO₂, CO, H₂, CH₄, NH₃)

Water Recovery System:

· Urine processing: Vapor compression distillation (ISS heritage)
· Recovery rate: 85% of urine to potable water
· Humidity condensate: Coolant condensing heat exchanger
· Recovery rate: 100% of cabin humidity
· Water polishing: Multi-filtration + UV sterilization
· Storage: 5,000 L buffer tanks (7-day reserve)

Waste Management:

· Solid waste: Compaction + vitrification (volume reduction 10:1)
· Byproducts: CO₂ and H₂O from oxidation available for recovery
· Microbial control: Periodic high-temperature sterilization cycle
· Storage capacity: 90 days of waste for 32 persons

Bioregenerative Components (Experimental):

· Hydroponics: 200 m² grow area (40% of caloric needs)
· Species: Lettuce, tomatoes, wheat, soy, spirulina
· Fish culture: 10,000 L aquaponics (tilapia, 20% of protein)
· Mycelium production: 50 m³ for protein and material production
· Integration: O₂ production, CO₂ consumption, water purification

Power Requirements:

· Normal operation: 85 kW continuous
· Peak loads: 120 kW (during experiments)
· Primary source: Solar arrays with 500 kWh battery bank
· Backup: Nuclear Stirling generators (10 kW each, 4 units)
· Redundancy: N+2 for critical systems

Control Systems:

· Automation: 95% autonomous operation
· Monitoring: 2,000 sensors throughout system
· AI management: Predictive maintenance, optimization algorithms
· Manual override: Physical controls for all critical functions
· Training mode: Can simulate failures for student practice

Safety Systems:

· Fire suppression: Water mist + CO₂ for electrical fires
· Rapid decompression: Shelter-in-place compartments throughout
· Radiation shelter: 30 cm water-equivalent shielding around sleeping quarters
· Medical: Integrated telemedicine with surgical capability
· Escape: 4 pressurized rovers for surface evacuation

Testing and Validation:

· All systems tested to TRL 6 before student exposure
· 1,000-hour continuous operation test before deployment
· Failure mode testing: 50 documented fault injections
· Student training begins with simple systems, progresses to full complexity

